President Obama has announced his intent to nominate Richard Stengel as Member and Chairman of the Broadcasting Board of Governors. Stengel is currently the Under Secretary of State for Public Diplomacy and Public Affairs, and has previously served as the Managing Editor of TIME magazine. He has also written several books and collaborated with Nelson Mandela on his autobiography. 

President Obama has also announced his intent to appoint several individuals to key Administration posts. These include Tam O'Shaughnessy and Amanda Wright Lane as Members of the Advisory Board of the National Air and Space Museum. O'Shaughnessy is the Executive Director of Sally Ride Science and the surviving partner of Dr. Sally Ride, the first American woman to fly in space. Wright Lane is a Trustee for The Wright Brothers Family Foundation and the great-grandniece of Orville and Wilbur Wright.

Susan Hayman has been appointed as a Member of the Board of Visitors to the United States Merchant Marine Academy. She currently serves as Vice President of Health, Safety, Quality and the Environment at Foss Maritime Company. 

Jacob Horowitz, Jim St. Germain, and Dr. Francisco A. Villarruel have been appointed as Members of the Coordinating Council on Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Prevention. Horowitz is the Policy Director for the Public Safety Performance Project at The Pew Charitable Trusts, St. Germain is the Residential Care Advocate for New York City's Administration for Children Services, and Dr. Villarruel is the Associate Chair for Education and Outreach at Michigan State University.

Tawara D. Goode and Dr. Rebecca S. Salon have been appointed as Members of the President's Committee for People with Intellectual Disabilities. Goode is the Director of the National Center for Cultural Competence at Georgetown University, and Salon is the Project Director at the National Center on Leadership for the Employment and Economic Advancement of People with Disabilities.